-- Hungary Stocks: Mol, OTP Bank, Drugmaker Egis Move in Budapest
-- B y   K r y s t o f   C h a m o n i k o l a s   a n d   E d i t h   B a l a z s
-- 2012-06-15T15:37:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-15/hungary-stocks-refiner-mol-drugmaker-egis-move-in-budapest.html
Hungary’s  BUX (BUX)  stock index climbed
2.4 percent to close at 17,256.16 in Budapest, bringing its
gains this week to 1.4 percent.  The following were among the most active equities in the
Hungarian market today. Stock symbols follow company names.  OTP Bank Nyrt. (OTP)   gained 3.2 percent to 3,540 forint,
jumping the most since May 18. Hungary’s largest lender advanced
after Prime Minister Viktor Orban said today that official talks
on an International Monetary Fund-led loan may start “any
moment.”  Hungary will submit a new central bank law to
Parliament next week to meet conditions set by international
lenders for bailout talks, Mihaly Varga, Hungary’s chief
negotiator for the aid, said in a televised interview today.  Mol Nyrt. (MOL)  , Hungary’s largest refiner, gained 2.1
percent to 16,160 forint, paring weekly losses to 2 percent. Oil
advanced for a second day on optimism that central banks will
take steps to boost economies.  Egis Gyogyszergyar Nyrt. (EGIS)   jumped 4 percent to
14,565 forint, the most since November, snapping a five-day
drop. Clinical trials of a biosimilar rheumatoid arthritis
medicine developed by South Korean partner Celltrion Inc.
yielded “positive results,” the drugmaker owned by
Laboratoires Servier said late yesterday.  To contact the reporters on this story:
